{% if failure_type == "CompileError" %}
The bind module has a compile error. The diagnosis above classifies every flagged identifier:
- **EXISTS as port**: use that exact name and direction — do not rename it
- **EXISTS as internal signal**: it is not a port; reference it only if the bind module can legally access it
- **NOT FOUND in module IR**: this is a hallucinated name — replace it with a real port from the "Module Ports" list above

Additional syntax rules to check:
- Replace any `assert property(...)` with `assert(...)` inside an always block
- Remove any `property`, `sequence`, `default clocking`, `disable iff`, `|->`, `|=>`
- Remove any `function`, `task`, or `class` declarations; rewrite as `wire`/`assign`
- Ensure the always block is `always @(posedge clk) begin ... end`
- Ports in the bind module spec header must match the DUT ports exactly
{% elif failure_type == "FormalFail" %}
The counterexample trace above shows the exact signal values that triggered the violation.
Fix the failing assertions using that trace:
- Read the signal values at each step to understand what the DUT actually does
- Correct the guard condition or the expected expression — the property logic, the
  timing (off-by-one in $past), or a missing qualifying condition
- Use `$past(<sig>)` for one-cycle-ago values with a `$past(1'b1)` validity guard
- Do NOT weaken assertions to make them vacuously true; do NOT remove assertions
- Do NOT introduce SVA property syntax
{% else %}
Fix the failing assertions. Check:
- Signal names match the module ports exactly
- Always blocks use `always @(posedge clk) begin ... end`
- No SVA property syntax (`property`, `|->`, `##N`, etc.)
{% endif %}

